#### Issue description

When using the ``PYBIND11_OVERLOAD`` macro, the compiler MSVC 14 2015 chokes when the output type is something like ``std::pair<double, double>`` and yields an obscure error about a problem with a "*" symbol.  I suspect the same problem would manifest with most STL types.  A workaround is a typedef which seems to placate the compiler

#### Reproducible example code

**Bad**:
``` C++
class PyVLEIsolineTracer : public VLEIsolineTracer {
public:
    /* Inherit the constructors */
    using VLEIsolineTracer::VLEIsolineTracer;

    std::pair<double, double> get_integration_limits() override {
        // Release the GIL
        py::gil_scoped_release release;
        {
            // Acquire GIL before calling Python code
            py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;

            // Parameters to macro are: Return type, parent class, name of function in C++, argument(s)
            PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(std::pair<double, double>, 
                              VLEIsolineTracer, 
                              get_integration_limits, 
                              // No arguments
                              );
        }
    }
};
```

**Good**:
``` C++
class PyVLEIsolineTracer : public VLEIsolineTracer {
public:
    /* Inherit the constructors */
    using VLEIsolineTracer::VLEIsolineTracer;

    std::pair<double, double> get_integration_limits() override {
        // Release the GIL
        py::gil_scoped_release release;
        {
            // Acquire GIL before calling Python code
            py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;

            // Parameters to macro are: Return type, parent class, name of function in C++, argument(s)
            typedef std::pair<double, double> pairdoubledouble;
            PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(pairdoubledouble, 
                              VLEIsolineTracer, 
                              get_integration_limits, 
                              // No arguments
                              );
        }
    }
};
```

